name: Hell's Kitchen Funky 80s Hideaway!
description:
Stay in the Heart of NYC. A 15 minute walk to Times Square, you'll be staying in one of the hippest neighborhoods in Manhattan -- Hell's Kitchen!!

** I'm also Fully Vaccinated. I had my Pfizer double-shot. My 2nd dose was April 1st, 2021. I've also been triple-boosted**
neighborhood_overview:
Bursting with energy and devilish charisma, Hell's Kitchen continues to evolve as high-rises move in and crooked characters move out. This classic New York City neighborhood is near it all—theaters on Broadway, green lawns in Central Park, and revered mom-and-pop culinary mainstays. As a storied NYC haunt, Hell's Kitchen lives up to its unmistakable mystique.

No visit to the neighborhood is complete without a visit to RUDY's Bar (9th Ave & 45th St) where you MUST order a blonde (or red head if you like them), and eat a few pigs. Just trust me on this... If you wanna nicer place to hang-out at, I recommend the PONY (10th Ave & 45th St). They have the best fried pickles in the city, and some Great selections of Craft beer, some of which are as high as 12% ABV!!

Want some more ideas for restaurants, bars, clubs, and other fun places to visit in the hood? Just ask me!!
host_about:
Hi!  I'm an extroverted Native New Yorker with a deep appreciation for the arts who likes meeting interesting new people, so of course I love Airbnb!!  I truly love living in this multi-cultured and ever changing metropolis.  ** I'm also Fully Vaccinated. I had my Pfizer double-shot. My 2nd dose was April 1st, 2021. **

My girlfriend and I are experienced travelers, always looking for new adventures.  3 years ago we finally made it to Alaska.  We spent a month backpacking around the country (no, you can't just call it a state).  A high point was trekking through Denali and getting caught in the first snowstorm of the season.  Quite a story there. 

I'm a big thrifter and know how to live cheaply in this overly expensive city.  Wanna see a Broadway show?  Let me know as I might be able to get you cheap tickets.  I can also tell you about lots of other ways to see and do things inexpensively in this crazy town.

WELCOME TO NYC!

neighborhood_overview:
THE NEIGHBORHOOD:

Carroll Gardens is truly a gem of a neighborhood. It is the very picture of the kind of charming and unique local culture that makes Brooklyn so desirable. It is characterized by its locally-owned businesses (from long-standing Italian eateries to trendy new restaurants), excellent schools, well-tended parks, a plethora of restaurants and bars, and block after block of tree-lined streets with beautiful brownstones.

Within a radius of a few blocks of our building you will find multiple grocers (including organic and health food purveyors), wine shops, yoga and pilates studios, boutiques and antique stores, Italian bakeries and gelato stands. And you are steps away from every kind of restaurant and café and bar you could want -- from hot new spots to long-standing family-run establishments, loads of authentic Italian fare, Thai, Ethiopian, Mexican, Japanese, French, Southern, Middle Eastern, fabulous brunch joints, juice bars, vegan joints, choco
host_about: I'm a writer and professor. I write about experimental and political art, social movements, and social theory. I love to travel and have spent time in many places in Latin America, as well as some places in Europe and Southeast Asia.  I'm a very easy-going guest; usually, I want to be out and about, and if I stay in, it's to read or write.

neighborhood_overview: Fort Greene, is one of the most diverse and safe neighborhoods in Brooklyn, if not NYC. It gets better every year! Downtown proper, which is less residential is down the road; it is changing at a fast pace. The latest addition to the neighborhood is City Point, a large, commercial and residential development. Once you step into  Fort Greene, you are entering one of the most after-sought, diverse and dynamic neighborhoods in the entire city. Fort Greene Park is the crown jewel of the neighborhood. The neighborhood is flanked South by Atlantic Terminal, Barclay's Center. To the North is the historical Brooklyn Navy Yard, epicenter of the USA's naval history. To the East you could find the Pratt Institute and the equally charming neighborhoods of Clinton Hill and Bedstuy. To the West is Downtown Brooklyn and Brooklyn Heights of course. Most subway lines stop by within a ten-minute walk radius.

neighborhood_overview:
Old style neighbourliness prevails on our block. The neighborhood
is not gentrified - yet, and as a traditional Bed Stuy street it may not be as clean as your suburban street. There is a Lincoln Market three blocks away, various bodegas, some good coffee shops, a handy Duane Reed pharmacy, but Bed Stuy isn't the upper West Side.

If you decide to stay in my apartment, it will be because you like the look of the apartment and its proximity to the subway, and because you like authentic, gritty, diverse, mixed income neighborhoods.

We like our neighborhood a lot, and after 10 years we have had no safety issues, day or night. The block has lots of new trees, planted as part of Bloomberg's One Million Trees program. We are members- and enjoy the Vernon Cases Community garden on the block.

Question: chickens rabbit cage with a total of 15, 40 feet, have a few chickens and rabbits? 
Answer: 
Assuming: chickens and rabbits are well trained. Whistle one time , chickens and rabbits lift one foot .
The number of feet left: 40-15 = 25 ( only )
And then whistle again , they all lift one foot .
The number of feet left: 25-15 = 10 ( only )
Now all chickens fell, all rabbits are still standing . 
Therefore, all feet are rabbits' feet
∴ rabbit number = 10 ÷ 2 = 5 ( only )
The number of chickens = 15-5 = 10 ( only )
Hahaha, I like it!

I also love to travel in the US and internationally, and think AirBNB has been lovely for exploring new places off the beaten path a bit.

neighborhood_overview:
Ditmas Park is located in a historic beautiful Brooklyn neighborhood. It is an old neighborhood founded by the dutch in the 17th century. The homes are victorian detached homes and include "mini-mansions". The streets are lined with grand trees and well-maintained gardens. The main commercial street has many restaurants, bars and excellent supermarkets with a farmers market every weekend. Historic Prospect Park is a 10-minute bike away. The newly renovated Kings Theater is a 5-minute walk from the apartment.
The neighborhood is richly diverse and true of a Brooklyn neighborhood. There is so much to do in Brooklyn that most people prefer to play here than Manhattan.

We also own another home in gorgeous Narrowsburg, NY which is also listed on Airbnb under Pepe Rosso Lodge.

host_about: Hello, I am an art historian, runner, and long-time resident of New York City--I was born in the village and I've been living in Brooklyn Heights since 2006. As I have been living elsewhere recently, my apartment has been empty for a few months. I prefer long-duration stays.

name: Funky 3 Bedroom Duplex in hip Greenpoint, Brooklyn
description: This is a funky duplex 3 bedroom apartment that sleeps 8. There is a large kitchen on the ground floor with access to the back yard. The master bedroom has a super comfy king size bed and the second bedroom queen size bed. The third bedroom has a full size bed. The living room folds out to an over-sized comfortable queen bed. The kitchen has an alcove that has an single airbed.
neighborhood_overview:
Just north of Williamsburg, Greenpoint has a tangible sense of community in both decades old businesses and more recent openings. Nearby 109 Franklin St, is a vintage furniture store that focuses on pieces from he 1970's. Boxy wooden cabinets, platform sofas, macrame wall hangings and 8 track friendly stereo's. 174 Franklin St is where you can also find Vintage clothes for men and women.

On Manhattan Ave is Peter Pans Doughnut and pastry store - try the velvet cupcakes! If you want a different and unusual place to go for dinner, I recommend Selamat Pagi on Driggs Ave. The food is Balinese and it is absolutely delicious. They make amazing cocktails and the prices are reasonable. Its rated 9.4 on Yelp!!!

name: Lovely Brooklyn Brownstone Garden Apartment
description:
Relax and recharge in a beautiful Brownstone Garden Floor Apartment with period detail & modern design.

Our early 1900's Queen Anne Brownstone studio in historic Bedford Stuyvesant is ideal for a single guest or couple. Located on a tree lined, residential block bordering Clinton Hill. Close to fantastic restaurants, bars, cafes, a park and more.

neighborhood_overview:
From Tripsavvy:

The sprawling Brooklyn neighborhood is known as Bedford-Stuyvesant, or Bed-Stuy is comprised of two historically different areas, Bedford, and the historically more upscale Stuyvesant. Parts of the neighborhood are landmarked so the remarkable late-19th-century feel of this area will be preserved. That means you can expect to see rows of gracious brownstone homes on tree-lined streets, lots of open sky (the buildings aren't more than four or five stories high), and historic buildings including churches and a small, old-fashioned community library.

In the past decade, the area has become a haven for artists and young families.

History:
Long a bastion of New York City’s African American community, Bed-Stuy, like Harlem, has had a mixed population of homeowners and renters. Bedford Stuyvesant (along with other neighborhoods such as Fort Greene) has been an important political and cultural hub of black life in New York City.

name: Chic Apartment in East Harlem
description:
Beautiful Harlem Apartment.
My lovely home, with just me & my cat Phred, (no other guests will be present) has a recently renovated bath & kitchen. With windows facing 3 directions, its a charming, sunny space, with eastern, western, and southern exposures.
Your cozy, private 100 sq. ft. bedroom has wall to wall glass, with sweeping neighborhood views.
neighborhood_overview: Spanish Harlem is diverse, multicultural, and friendly. Also known as the Barrio, the area is blessed with dozens of community gardens, ranging from simple homespun rustic, to modern architectural sleek. And more murals grace our walls than any neighborhood in Manhattan! We also seem to have more street fairs, parades and festivals as well. Walk west past Pleasant Avenue, and you'll find a lovely promenade on the East River. A block or two south, and you're in Thomas Jefferson Park, home to one of the city's largest outdoor public swimming pools.
host_about:
I am lazy, yet industrious; bright, though not learned; outgoing, but a bit shy. I'm told I'm generous. I work well with others. I'm a good talker. I'm a good listener. 
My greatest joy is drawing and painting. And I love designing things. Cars, houses, alarm clocks, locomotives, shoes, chairs, lawn mowers, book covers, etc., etc. I've been into design since I was 8 or 9 years old. 
   I do believe in a higher power, and though I'm devoted, I'm not religious. What I look for in a friend is honesty, kindness, humor, and curiosity. I love people. They're my favorite mammal. Well, next to my cat, Phred.
  I enjoy hosting and am fairly good at it. I keep a tidy home, but when expecting a guest, I take the opportunity to fine tune my home. It's a chance to take care of those little chores that have been getting put off.  
   I like to travel. I enjoyed backpacking and youth hostels in my 20's and small elegant hotels as an adult. Or, on occasion, renting a house, as I did in Rome and Venice,  My favorite destinations have been Tokyo, Rome, Aspen and Berlin. 
   I love science fiction, interior design, cocktail parties, vintage cars, and fine menswear. I'm currently reading "Save the Cat", a book on screenwriting, and "The Professor and the Madman", a tale of murder, insanity, and the making of the Oxford English Dictionary.  My favorite movie: 2001, A Space Odysey. Show: Caberet. Music: Modern Jazz. Food: Seafood Gumbo.  
   As an Airbnb host, my intention is to create a customized experience for my guest. This can be a quiet, book lined sanctuary, a lively Manhattan pad, or anything in between.  When I ask how was your day, it is because I am sincerely interested. I know that, for some, being away from home can be disorienting. So it's important for me that I be there for you if needed, or remain unobtrusive  if you'd prefer.
If I have a goal, it's that every space I occupy throughout my life be improved by my having been there.
Edit

description: Charming, spacious, private 'Tea Room' with Kitchen  and Laundry in Brooklyn. Location cannot be beaten. Subway lines within closing proximity will take you to Manhattan in 15 minutes. neighborhood_overview: Fort Greene, is one of the most diverse and safe neighborhoods in Brooklyn, if not NYC. It gets better every year! Downtown proper, which is less residential is down the road; it is changing at a fast pace. The latest addition to the neighborhood is City Point, a large, commercial and residential development. Once you step into  Fort Greene, you are entering one of the most after-sought, diverse and dynamic neighborhoods in the entire city. Fort Greene Park is the crown jewel of the neighborhood. The neighborhood is flanked South by Atlantic Terminal, Barclay's Center. To the North is the historical Brooklyn Navy Yard, epicenter of the USA's naval history. To the East you could find the Pratt Institute and the equally charming neighborhoods of Clinton Hill and Bedstuy. To the West is Downtown Brooklyn and Brooklyn Heights of course. Most subway lines stop by within a ten-minute walk radius.

neighborhood_overview:
Here, an overview from TimeOut magazine.
The West Village manages to preserve a low-key, everyone-knows-everyone feel and picturesque charm. Only here could West 10th Street cross West 4th Street, and Waverly Place cross…Waverly Place. The area’s bohemian population may have dwindled years ago, but a few old landmarks remain. Raise a glass in the White Horse Tavern, a favorite of such literary luminaries as Ezra Pound, Norman Mailer and Dylan Thomas, or enjoy a jazz set at the legendary Village Vanguard. While the gay scene has largely migrated north, the West Village played a pivotal role in the gay-rights movement, and many shops, bars and restaurants along Christopher Street from Sheridan Square to the Hudson River pier are out, loud and proud, including the historic Stonewall Inn.

neighborhood_overview:
Compass neighborhood guide describes it the best: Williamsburg has become an area known for its trendsetting neighbors and storefronts, which has promoted Brooklyn-branded shops, bars, and restaurants.

Williamsburg’s music scene draws an audience from all five boroughs. Large venues like Brooklyn Bowl or Music Hall of Williamsburg attract big name acts, while smaller venues like 285 Kent and Shea Stadium are at the forefront of the do-it-yourself music scene. Here, die-hard punk, rock, and experimental fans can enjoy live acts with more intimacy.

In Williamsburg, the party often starts early in the day and continues late into the night. Many bars have outdoor spaces that become packed when the sun is out. Under-the-radar promoters host daytime pop-up parties at all different kinds of venues: parking lots, rooftops, lofts, or parks.

Nightlife here is comprised of chic lounges and popular dive bars with backyard patios. Down-home bars like Turkey’s Nest
host_about:
Hi, I'm Anna!  I'm a fellow traveler, musician and yogi. I've been part of the Airbnb community since 2011.

With a deep love for travel and connection, our passion is to create memorable vacations that bring friends and family together. Our priority is to ensure you feel completely comfortable and at home. 

Beyond hospitality, our dream is to strengthen the community through youth education programs, shaping a brighter future together.

Bedroom and living room accommodate 3 people in each, offering extra sofas and great sunlight on a tree-lined street. Spotless kitchen with standard amenities, always stocked with ice, coffee, and tea service. High speed Wifi, and dining table for 4 that doubles as a desk with good natural light.

neighborhood_overview:
Located in the heart of historic Greenwich Village, you have the best of New York in walking distance. Alicia Keys & Robert Deniro grew up here.

Two blocks from stunning Washington Square Park, and one block from SoHo--the most fashionable nabe in town.

This part of the city remains a historic cultural center--Melville lived here and stars like Mariska Hargitay still do. The best comedians in the world pop in to the Comedy Cellar every week, restaurants like L'Artusi offer meals you will truly never forget, and the classic jazz clubs (Vanguard, Smalls, Blue Note) where Bird, Monk, and Streisand all performed are still going strong. Join us for an excellent time!
host_about:
I'm from Manhattan, and sometimes travel for my work as a corporate advisor and management consultant. As a guest, I am very flexible. I make new friends easily and enjoy my alone time too.

I have traveled and lived in many cities in the US and abroad. My favorite place is still New York and I have a soft spot for the Great Lakes. Vienna, Beijing, and Guatemala City can be lots of fun too. 

Always enjoy meeting people of diverse backgrounds, and connecting on things we share.  I like lots of different kinds of music: Bach for work, alternative rock for the ride home, new/tonal works for pleasure.  Interests include good books and restoring vintage motorcycles.

name: STUNNING-LUXURY Two Bed in Fashionable Brooklyn
description:
This spectacular corner apartment has a spacious wrap around private terrace, that offers beautiful unobstructed views of the Brooklyn & Manhattan skyline.

It's a short 5-10-minute walk to Prospect Park, which was designed by the same architects (Frederick Olmstead & Calvert Vaux); who designed New York's Central Park.

The Q & B trains are 3 blocks away & It's a 20-25-minute ride to Manhattan.
neighborhood_overview:
A vibrant and diverse neighborhood. A few blocks from Prospect Park and a 20 minute-ride on the subway, to Manhattan.

Located ten minutes walking from Kings Theatre which has many live shows and concerts. There is public parking in my property.

There is a butcher across the street. A fishmonger a few doors down. Plenty of fresh vegetables in nearby shops. If you happen to stay over a weekend, there is an excellent Farmers Market, that opens each Saturday in Prospect Park. The market has all sorts of farm fresh produce, as well as plants and flowers. They also sell homemade organic breads and pastries.

Prospect Park has horseback riding. Horseback riding has a long history in Prospect Park. The 3.5-mile bridle path features scenic and varying terrain. Brooklyn equine at Prospect Park Stable, located just outside the park across from the Parade Ground, offers horses for rental, riding classes for all levels, pony rides and parties. Welcome to our home!

Astoria is a vibrant, safe, fun neighborhood. Our quiet street is close to shops, restaurants and bars, and a short ten-minute walk to the Astoria-Ditmars subway station (15 minutes to Manhattan).

neighborhood_overview: Time Out has called Astoria one of the ten coolest neighborhoods in the world, and we don’t disagree. Our house is on a very quiet street but within a few blocks you will find dozens of restaurants, bars, and shops catering to all kinds of interests and budgets. Food and pharmacies are available 24-hours. There are several parks and playgrounds nearby, the largest being Astoria Park on the waterfront with rolling lawns overlooking the city skyline as well as a running track, outdoor gym, playground, soccer field, skate park, and an Olympic-size swimming pool in summer. Public transportation is easy here, with subways, buses, and Citibikes all great options to get you around. We’re 10-15 minutes from LGA and 30 minutes to JFK by cab (subject to traffic, of course).

name: Woodhaven Artist Studio
description: Welcome to Woodhaven. Our studio offers travelers a place to rest after a day of galivanting around NYC. We are less than a block from the WOODHAVEN BLVD "J" Subway stop which whisks you into Manhattan in 30 minutes and is centrally located between JFK and LGA airports. Our neighborhood offers diverse ethnic food typical of Queens and grocery stores for home cooking. Woodhaven is also home to Forest Park, which offers outdoor recreation.
neighborhood_overview: Woodhaven is a historic neighborhood located in the center of Queens. It is located on the "J" subway line, which links to many other subway lines, making the city easily accessible via public transportation for commuters and tourists alike. whisking you into the hustle and bustle of Manhattan in 30 minutes.  Woodhaven is also known for its large, beautiful park, "Forest Park."   It is about 538 acres and has everything from hiking trails, tennis, basketball, handball courts, playgrounds, baseball fields, track field, a skate park, horseback riding, and even a bandshell with summer activities almost every night. Historically Woodhaven and Forest Park share the novelty of hosting "The Forest Park Carousel" dating from 1890 and is one of two carousels from master carver Daniel Mueller. And our favorite Woodhaven claim to fame is Neir's Tavern, the oldest bar in New York City and it's an easy 15-minute walk from the Studio!!! AND a perk of being right off Woodhaven Blvd. is Rockaway Beach
host_about: I am a collage Artist and active community builder in Woodhaven, as well as a stay-at-home mother of two adorable active children. My husband, Jhonny is a superintendent in DUMBO, coach to his children's soccer teams and actively renovating our castle (home).

name: Lovely 2-Bedroom with Shared Garden in Brooklyn
description: Kick back in this garden level walk-through in a historical 2-unit 1890’s brownstone in Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood. Enjoy shared access to the garden, where you can eat, drink, or relax. Enjoy the private kitchen, bathroom, garden-facing bedroom, and living room/bedroom (2 bedrooms, total). neighborhood_overview:
Since the late 1930s, Bedford–Stuyvesant has been a stronghold of Black culture. Nicknamed “Brooklyn’s Little Harlem.” Musicians, performers and artists including Jay-Z, Tracy Morgan, Chris Rock, Mike Tyson and Lil’ Kim, grew up in this historic neighborhood. The neighborhood remains a home for many artists, actors, and musicians, which is reflected in Bed-Stuy’s vibrant cultural and culinary scene.

neighborhood_overview:
Astoria is a thriving neighborhood in Queens teeming with a diversity of people, shops, and restaurants. It was named after John Astor, the nation’s first multi-millionaire.

Home to Little Egypt and the largest Greek community outside of Greece, excellent Middle Eastern and Greek food abounds. But Astoria also boasts so much more food—Colombian, Czech, Thai, Italian, Indian, Peruvian, and a centuries-old beer garden (The Bohemian Hall).

Steinway Piano Company was born in Astoria in 1870 and is still here! Take a tour and see how these world-famous pianos are made.

Noguchi Museum is in Astoria. Love modern art and design? Don’t miss visiting.

Astoria Park runs along the East River and offers amazing views of the Manhattan Skyline, not to mention the largest pool in the city. Grab some delicious takeout, find a table overlooking the river, and dine with a view.

Hi, I'm Jennifer!

I love Astoria, it's a fantastic neighborhood to live in and visit. Hope you choose to book a stay at my place!

Perfectly located 1 bedroom apartment in the heart of the West Village neighborhood on historic Cornelia Street.

Steps from dozens of incredible restaurants, bars, cafes, jazz venues, comedy clubs, and shops.

1 minute walk from the A, C, E, B, D, and F trains. 5 minute walk from 1, 2, 3, and L trains.

neighborhood_overview: The West Village draws fashionable crowds to its designer boutiques and trendy restaurants. Quaint streets, some still cobblestoned, are lined with Federal-style townhouses and dotted with public squares. Notable venues include the Village Vanguard jazz club and the Stonewall Inn bar, site of the 1969 riots that launched the gay rights movement. The historically arty area also has piano bars, cabarets and theaters.

neighborhood_overview: Sunset Park is a wonderful multicultural neighborhood with lots going on nearby! It's a busy neighborhood but our block is surprisingly tranquil, very quiet at night with a neighborly residential feel. We are two blocks from Industry City with endless shopping, bars, restaurants, and events. 5 blocks to Sunset Park, a large park with playgrounds, a public pool, and beautiful views of the sunset and Manhattan skyline. It's also one block from historic Greenwood Cemetery. The subway is only one block away and it's an express stop (D, N, and R trains) so it’s very fast into Manhattan. Lots of great great restaurants and bars within walking distance, and a bowling alley on the corner.

Avail 12/20-1/17 by the week.

neighborhood_overview: Bushwick is just east of Williamsburg and a quick 20 minutes into Manhattan. A few pocket parks are shaded by mature trees and have playgrounds."

Keep it simple at this peaceful and centrally-located private room in Brooklyn, NY. Only 1-minute walk to the train station and 15-minute ride via J Train to Manhattan!

The place has the basics with just the right amount of creativity. Making it ideal for those traveling to the fast paced tourist destinations of NYC yet wants to have a little tranquility afterwards.

This is a private room in a 3-bedroom unit w/ the bathroom shared with other guests.
neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood is a mix of family and singles working in Manhattan. There is a RiteAid, Dunkin Donuts, Popeyes and Dominos right around the corner where the J Train is located.

Location is really accessible going to Queens, Manhattan, JFK and other parts of Brooklyn.
host_about:
Hi! I’m Michael. A videographer by profession, by hobby and by passion.

Here sharing with you our semi-basement private room personally designed by me. Nothing super special about it but kinda going for something simple yet creative. Should you need an awesome travel vlog/highlight film of your vacation, well look no further. :)

Hope you enjoy your here, in Brooklyn and wherever in NYC!

neighborhood_overview:
East New York was founded as the Town of New Lots in the 1650s. It was annexed as the 26th Ward of the rapidly growing city of Brooklyn in 1886, and became part of New York City in 1898. During the latter part of the twentieth century, East New York came to be predominantly inhabited by African Americans and Latinos.

East New York is part of Brooklyn Community District 5, and its primary ZIP Codes are 11207, 11208, and 11239.[1] It is patrolled by the 75th Precinct of the New York City Police Department.[4] New York City Housing Authority (NYCHA) property in the area is patrolled by P.S.A. 2. Coverage by the Fire Department of New York is provided by Battalions 39 & 44. Politically it is represented by the New York City Council's 37th and 42nd Districts.

Wikipedia publication.

Between the parks, the riverside, and the bustling streets, the Upper West Side is a walker's paradise. While you’re out exploring, make sure to check out the many trails through Central Park. Before you hit the park, stop in at a local bodega for picnic supplies. Later, you’ll find an endless supply of chill bistros and bars in the neighborhood. Compared to its bordering areas, the Theater District, Hell’s Kitchen, and Harlem, the Upper West Side has a more laid-back, early-to-bed, early-to-rise kind of vibe. neighborhood_overview:
Hell's Kitchen, also known as Clinton, is a vibrant neighborhood on the West Side of Manhattan, bordered by 34th Street to 59th Street and from 8th Avenue to the Hudson River. Historically a gritty area, Hell's Kitchen has transformed into a bustling and trendy district, while retaining much of its old-school charm. The neighborhood is characterized by its diverse mix of residents, ranging from artists and actors to young professionals and long-time locals.

Its proximity to the Theater District and Broadway gives it a creative and dynamic energy, with numerous rehearsal spaces, acting studios, and small theaters peppered throughout the area. Hell's Kitchen boasts a vibrant food scene, from casual eateries and food trucks to high-end restaurants offering global cuisine, particularly along 9th Avenue, where you can find everything from authentic ethnic food to New York-style delis.

Bathed in morning light, high ceilings, this peaceful retreat overlooks a quiet garden. Enjoy whisper-quiet AC, strong showers, fast WiFi, and a bookshelf of literary classics. Cook in the fully-stocked kitchen and gather around a rustic dining table. Nestled on the second floor of a charming walk-up, it’s the perfect spot for a tranquil stay in the heart of the iconic West Village.
